Sasalin shot a burst of fire, and the tall Slak creature set a small patch of forest ablaze, then circled above, watching for the right moment. Oddly enough, when he slowed down, the strange screeching sound behind him also stopped. Sasalin forgot he had a passenger on his back.
"Come on, Tenuk, you've transformed into a Slak before!"
"There's a big difference between flying on your own and being suddenly dragged away by a huge pink dragon!"
"Not bad, Kael?"
Kael clearly disagreed with Nise's statement. He looked paler than usual, and his claws were deeply embedded in Sasalin's back, drawing blood from the Slak. Yet Sasalin didn't seem to mind. Nevertheless, Sasalin realized he had scared his new friend and landed on an open space.
"Sorry, sorry, I smelled a smell. I need to deal with it!"
"You had to drag us along too?" Tenuk slid down from Sasalin's back and along his tail to the ground, asking in a sharp tone. "We left Retwick behind! We abandoned that strong, aggressive big guy! How is he supposed to find us?"
"He'll figure it out..." Nise nodded approvingly. "Retwick is slow, but not dumb."
"Then does Retwick know how to drive?"
Nise blinked his eyes and turned to look at Tenuk. "Of course he knows how to drive."
"Have you ever seen Retwick drive a car? He doesn't have a truck like yours, and I've never seen him drive a cute little car like Kael's. He started driving to work purely because you always drove us to work. He only has a bicycle."
A burst of laughter interrupted them. Sasalin suddenly laughed uncontrollably, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took Sasalin a while to calm down.
"Sorry, sorry, I was just imagining it. Your big armored friend, riding a small bicycle designed for Temson children. That image was just too ridiculous! I wish I had telepathy. That idea was so amusing! I must treasure it well."
Kael also laughed because he could imagine what Sasalin was thinking about. "Alright, alright. But what did you smell? Why did you fly so fast?"
Sasalin grunted, took off, disappeared quickly, and then flew back, dropping a corpse in front of Nise. It was an Orotharak, a very rare golden-white dragon-like creature. But its head was missing. "Another one is dead. I heard their cries. I smelled their blood. I must protect them and hunt the murderer. This is the will of Ixini. Those creatures are nearby."
The powerful Slak suddenly froze. Nise and Kael also froze, their attention drawn to a gap at the edge of the clearing. A huge and dark creature was staring at them, making hissing sounds. The creature suddenly spread its two pairs of massive wings and rushed forward, aiming directly at Sasalin, completely ignoring the three small creatures between it and Sasalin. Kael and Tenuk barely managed to dodge aside, but Nise found herself dragged to the ground, almost flung onto Sasalin's back.
Sasalin grabbed Nise and used its long, agile tail to throw her onto its back, then took to the air. The black creature with two pairs of wings quickly chased after it.
Kael let out a grunt, pulled out his gun from behind his back, and then opened his bag, taking out a belt of bullets. He hung the belt around his chest for easy access, but soon realized that Nise, Sasalin, and the monster were all gone without a trace.
"Hey, Tenuk, can you transform into a flying animal?" Kael asked.
"Do you want to chase after them?"
“Nonsense.”
“But… one of them is a giant monster!”
“So what? My rifle here has strong firepower and can fire at any moment. I just need to see it, and I can bring it down.”
Tenuk hesitated for a moment, then took a step back, giving himself some space. With a low, slightly painful groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turned into scales, and his arms turned into wings. He soon transformed into an ordinary light-blue Slak, but his eyes remained red.
“Get on.”
Tenuk now looked like an ordinary Slak, with neatly arranged scales on his back and a pair of spikes for Kael to grab onto. It took Tenuk a long time to get airborne, but once he was in the air, he quickly adjusted his direction and tried to catch up as hard as he could.
However, Tenuk and Kael soon realized they weren't the only opponents. A second dark monster burst out from below them, and Tenuk barely dodged the impact.
"I guess this is the other terrible big monster that Larenex was worried about," Kael frowned, trying to shoot at the second monster, but he missed. He quickly reloaded.
Tenuk didn't respond. He was busy flying toward Nise and Sasalin, even though another monster was chasing them. Kael awkwardly turned around to face the monster. Since the monster was chasing them, Kael thought it was a good sign, because it made it easier for him to aim and shoot. Two bullets pierced through the monster's upper wing, and it howled in pain before disappearing into the forest. Kael wasn't sure if it was still following them, but he thought it was definitely too slow to keep up.
Up ahead, Sasalin was wildly flailing his body, spitting fire at the black monster. Nise desperately held onto Sasalin to prevent himself from falling. Although this monster was clearly injured, it seemed to be enraged and unwilling to retreat, and the fireballs didn't seem to be doing much damage. After stabilizing his body, Nise took out his trusted shotgun. Of course, the shotgun wouldn't be effective against such a monster, but the spread bullets at least could scare off this black beast, right?
